<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-12-14T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-12-14T22:00:00-05:00" n="178" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.3393/12–1548: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-15T11:00:00+08:00">December 15, 1948—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 15—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2517. Purpose surveillance your [<hi rend="italic">Taipei’s</hi>]
                                183<note n="5" xml:id="d178fn5">Sent to the Department as telegram
                                No. 93, December 8, midnight, <ref target="#pg_227">p.
                                227</ref>.</note> unclear. Please elucidate further. We do not
                            believe it advisable that US Navy should become involved in policing
                            Taiwan coast.</p>
                        <p>Sent Taipei 96, repeated Department.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>